## 🔑 Memory Taxonomy

### Explicit (Declarative) Memory
- **Hippocampus-dependent; consciously accessible**
- Requires intentional recall; disrupted by hippocampal lesions

| Type | Neural Substrate | Content | Key Features |
|------|-----------------|---------|--------------|
| **Episodic** | Right > left hippocampus; medial temporal lobe (MTL); prefrontal retrieval | Personal autobiographical events with temporal + spatial context ("what, when, where") | Time-stamped; highly context-dependent; vulnerable to interference; "mental time travel" |
| **Semantic** | Left > right; anterior/inferior temporal neocortex (temporal pole, fusiform, parahippocampal); less hippocampus-dependent over time | General world knowledge, facts, concepts, word meanings | Survives hippocampal damage after consolidation; degraded in semantic dementia (anterior temporal lobe atrophy) |

### Implicit (Nondeclarative) Memory
- **Hippocampus-independent; not consciously accessible; expressed through performance**

| Type | Neural Substrate | Content | Key Features |
|------|-----------------|---------|--------------|
| **Procedural / Skill** | Basal ganglia (habit: dorsal striatum); cerebellum (timing/adaptation); motor cortex | Motor skills (riding a bike), cognitive habits, stimulus-response learning | Preserved in amnesia (H.M. improved mirror tracing); degraded in Parkinson's/HD |
| **Priming** | Neocortex (modality-specific sensory areas) | Facilitated processing of previously seen/heard stimuli | Perceptual priming: occipital/temporal; conceptual priming: left temporal/frontal; preserved in amnesia and AD (early) |
| **Classical conditioning** | Amygdala (emotional/fear conditioning); cerebellum (eyeblink/somatic reflex conditioning) | Conditioned fear (CS→US pairing); conditioned reflexes | Amygdala lesions block fear conditioning but not eyeblink; cerebellar lesions block eyeblink but not fear |
| **Non-associative** | Spinal cord and brainstem circuits | Habituation (↓response to repeated stimuli), sensitization (↑response after strong stimulus) | Simplest form of learning; no cortex required |

