## 🔑 The Case of H.M. (Henry Molaison, 1926–2008)

William Beecher Scoville performed bilateral medial temporal lobectomy (hippocampus, amygdala, parahippocampal gyrus) in 1953 to treat intractable epilepsy. The resulting memory profile defined modern memory systems:

| Memory Function | H.M.'s Status | Conclusion |
|----------------|--------------|------------|
| Anterograde episodic memory | **Profoundly impaired** — could not form new explicit memories | Hippocampus essential for new explicit memory encoding/consolidation |
| Recent retrograde memory | Impaired (temporal gradient: recent > remote memory loss) | Hippocampus needed for consolidation of recent but not remote memories |
| Remote long-term semantic memory | **Preserved** | Once consolidated, semantic memory is hippocampus-independent |
| Short-term memory (STM) | **Preserved** (digit span ~6–7 normal) | STM / working memory independent of hippocampus |
| Procedural memory | **Preserved** — improved on mirror tracing task each day despite denying ever having done it | Procedural learning is hippocampus-independent |
| Priming | **Preserved** — showed normal priming on word-stem completion | Priming is hippocampus-independent |
| Personality and intelligence | **Preserved** | Hippocampus not required for personality, IQ, or general cognition |

