## 🔑 Memory Consolidation Theories

### Standard Model of Consolidation
- Initially, memories are stored in **hippocampus** (labile, context-rich)
- Over time (weeks–years), memories are **transferred to neocortex** and become hippocampus-independent
- Predicts: old memories survive hippocampal damage; recent memories are lost

### Multiple Trace Theory (MTT) — Nadel & Moscovitch
- **Episodic memories** always remain partially hippocampus-dependent (each retrieval creates a new trace)
- **Semantic memories** can become fully neocortex-dependent (hippocampus-independent)
- Explains: patients with hippocampal damage lose recent AND remote episodic detail but retain semantic gist
- Evidence: semantic dementia (anterior temporal lobe) = semantic memory loss with intact episodic

### Sleep and Memory Consolidation
| Sleep Stage | Memory Type Consolidated | Mechanism |
|------------|------------------------|----------|
| **SWS (N3)** | Declarative (episodic + semantic) | Hippocampal sharp-wave ripples (SWRs) at ~80–100 Hz → replay of daytime sequences; coordinated with cortical slow oscillations (0.5–1 Hz) and thalamic sleep spindles (12–15 Hz) → drives hippocampus-to-neocortex transfer |
| **REM sleep** | Procedural, emotional, fear extinction | Activated amygdala; acetylcholine surge; theta rhythm in hippocampus; emotional memory processing |
| **Sleep deprivation** | Impairs both declarative and procedural consolidation | ↓SWR density; ↓spindle-slow oscillation coupling; impaired next-day performance |

