## 🏥 Clinical Significance

| Condition | Key Pathology | Memory Profile | Key Features |
|-----------|--------------|---------------|--------------|
| **Anterograde amnesia** | Hippocampal/MTL damage (bilateral) | Cannot form new explicit memories; STM + procedural intact | H.M. prototype; seen in anoxia, herpes encephalitis, bilateral temporal strokes |
| **Retrograde amnesia** | Varies; temporal gradient | Loss of pre-injury memories, recent > remote (Ribot's law) | Head trauma, bilateral ECT; remote memories most resistant |
| **Korsakoff syndrome** | Thiamine (B1) deficiency → mammillary body + dorsomedial thalamus necrosis | Severe anterograde + retrograde amnesia; **confabulation** (unconscious gap-filling); intact procedural | Alcoholism most common; Wernicke's encephalopathy (acute: confusion + ophthalmoplegia + ataxia) precedes if untreated |
| **Transient global amnesia (TGA)** | Transient hippocampal dysfunction (venous ischemia/Valsalva) | Acute anterograde amnesia lasting <24h; retrograde amnesia for recent hours; repetitive questioning | Middle-aged adults; resolves completely; benign; DWI shows small hippocampal CA1 DWI lesion in ~70% at 24–72h |
| **Semantic dementia** | Anterior temporal lobe atrophy (FTLD-TDP-43) | Progressive loss of semantic memory (word meanings, object recognition); episodic relatively spared | Fluent aphasia (anomia, surface dyslexia); face and object recognition impaired; bilateral anterior temporal atrophy |
| **Alzheimer's disease (AD)** | Entorhinal cortex → hippocampus → neocortex (Braak stages); Aβ plaques + tau tangles; cholinergic deficit | Episodic memory (anterograde) first; then semantic, visuospatial, executive | Free recall >> recognition; cannot learn new information; cholinesterase inhibitors modestly helpful |
| **Psychogenic/Dissociative amnesia** | No structural lesion; emotional trigger or psychological trauma | Focal retrograde amnesia (autobiographical); anterograde normal; or fugue state | No DWI changes; reversible; diagnosis of exclusion |
| **Déjà vu** | Hippocampal hyperactivity; mismatch between familiarity and recognition circuits | Pathological in TLE; occasional déjà vu normal | Ictal déjà vu in mesial temporal lobe epilepsy — aura before complex partial seizure |

